---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { getAllReviews, sortReviews } from '../lib/data';
import { withBase } from '../lib/base';
import { brands } from '../config/brands';
import { withUtm } from '../lib/url';
import * as fs from 'fs';
import * as path from 'path';

const seasonConfig = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(path.join(process.cwd(), 'config', 'season.json'), 'utf8'));

const reviews = getAllReviews();
const sortedReviews = sortReviews(reviews);
const latestReview = sortedReviews[0]?.review;
const isFixtureMode = import.meta.env.JURYPRESS_DATA_MODE === 'fixture' || process.env.JURYPRESS_DATA_MODE === 'fixture';
const modelToShow = isFixtureMode 
  ? 'Demo fixture' 
  : (latestReview ? latestReview.model : seasonConfig.model);
---

<Layout
  title="Methodology | JuryPress"
  description="How JuryPress automatically selects, evaluates, scores, and publishes product reviews without human intervention."
>
  <div class="methodology-page">
    <h1>Methodology</h1>
    <p class="methodology-lead">
      JuryPress is fully automated. Every step — from product selection to article publication — 
      runs without human review. This page explains the process.
    </p>

    <section class="method-section">
      <h2>1. Deterministic selection</h2>
      <p>
        A product is chosen each day from a public source based on popularity metrics. 
        The source rotates by day of the week:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Monday:</strong> Hacker News Top</li>
        <li><strong>Tuesday:</strong> GitHub Breakout</li>
        <li><strong>Wednesday:</strong> Show HN</li>
        <li><strong>Thursday:</strong> Hugging Face Spaces</li>
        <li><strong>Friday:</strong> GitHub Developer Tools</li>
        <li><strong>Saturday:</strong> GitHub OSS</li>
        <li><strong>Sunday:</strong> Cross-source selection</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The product must have an identifiable name and a canonical URL. 
        Generic news articles, job postings, and non-software items are excluded by heuristic rules.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="method-section">
      <h2>2. Evidence collection</h2>
      <p>
        Evidence is gathered primarily from the official product source (repository, landing page, API metadata) 
        and the source discussion thread. Third-party reviews are strictly excluded.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="method-section">
      <h2>3. Evidence classification</h2>
      <p>
        The AI distinguishes between four types of information:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Verified fact:</strong> directly observable in the public evidence</li>
        <li><strong>Creator claim:</strong> stated by the product creator but not independently verified</li>
        <li><strong>Inference:</strong> a reasonable conclusion drawn by the AI</li>
        <li><strong>Unknown:</strong> information not available in the supplied evidence</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Each criterion receives a confidence rating (high, medium, low, or not assessable).
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="method-section">
      <h2>4. Five-person evaluation</h2>
      <p>
        Five distinct Judgie-AI personas evaluate the product simultaneously in a single AI call. 
        Each judge brings a different professional background and set of priorities.
      </p>
      <p>
        JuryPress uses the five personas and hackathon rubric defined
        by <a href={withUtm(brands.judgie.url, 'methodology_judgie')} class="method-brand-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener">{brands.judgie.name}</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        JuryPress runs its own automated publishing pipeline; it does not
        claim that {brands.judgie.name} independently reviewed or endorsed each article.
      </p>
      <div class="method-cta-box">
        <a href={withBase('/judges/')}>Meet the five judges →</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="method-section">
      <h2>5. Code-side score calculation</h2>
      <p>
        The AI provides raw scores (0–5) for each criterion. 
        Weighted scores and the Jury Score are recalculated server-side using fixed rubric weights. 
        The AI cannot influence the final score beyond the raw criterion scores.
      </p>
      <div class="method-cta-box">
        <a href={withBase('/rubric/')}>Explore the full rubric →</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="method-section">
      <h2>6. Automatic publication</h2>
      <p>
        The article is built as a static page and deployed without editorial review.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Model:</strong> {isFixtureMode ? 'Demo fixture' : `Current production model: ${modelToShow}`}</li>
        <li><strong>Season Version:</strong> {seasonConfig.name}</li>
        <li><strong>Human Review:</strong> None.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="method-section">
      <h2>7. Failure handling</h2>
      <p>
        If the AI generation fails validation (schema mismatch, prohibited phrases, missing evidence IDs, 
        or homogenized verdicts), the run retries up to 3 times. 
        If all retries fail, the run is logged and no article is published.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .methodology-page {
    padding: 1rem 0 2rem;
  }
  .methodology-page h1 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    color: #1a1a2e;
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }
  .methodology-lead {
    text-align: center;
    color: #666;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    max-width: 560px;
    margin: 0 auto 2rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
  .method-section {
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }
  .method-section h2 {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    color: #1a1a2e;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;
    padding-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  .method-section p {
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    color: #444;
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0.5rem 0;
  }
  .method-section ul {
    padding-left: 1.2rem;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    color: #444;
  }
  .method-section ul li {
    margin-bottom: 0.3rem;
  }
  .method-cta-box {
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
  .method-cta-box a {
    color: #c67c3b;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  .method-cta-box a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  .method-brand-link {
    color: #c67c3b;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .method-brand-link:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
</style>
